  "data": {
    "title": "Inès Chatin, Libération’s rue du Bac investigation, and France’s public reckoning",
    "excerpt": "After Libération put the rue du Bac investigation on the page, France's major broadcasters, regional archives, and the Paris Bar's dated columns picked up the thread from Paris to the Atlantic coast. This piece walks the dated record in sequence - who was named, who had to answer - and keeps allegations framed as allegations until any court says otherwise.",
    "subjects": [
      "Child sexual abuse",
      "France",
      "Libération",
      "Inès Chatin",
      "Paris"
    ],
    "content": [
      {
        "_type": "block",
        "style": "normal",
        "children": [
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "By early April 2026, much of France was talking about ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "Inès Chatin",
            "marks": [
              "em"
            ]
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": ", and the story kept moving through the rest of the month - dated interviews, revised reporting on the page, and regional archives shown on screen. What follows is that public record in time order, from a jointly published open letter in May 2025 through Libération's institutional line to the April 2026 broadcasts, so readers can see how accountability questions accumulated rather than landing as a single day's verdict. That kind of attention is never neutral for a survivor: it can bring solidarity, and it can bring scrutiny, distortion, and exhaustion. She did not arrive as an abstraction in a debate. She arrived as a woman willing to be heard.",
            "marks": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "_type": "block",
        "style": "normal",
        "children": [
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "If you do not follow French news closely, the dated sources already lay out a few fixed points. They name Inès Chatin. They place the main story in central Paris - the 7th arrondissement around rue du Bac and Saint-Germain-des-Prés. They follow a second thread to Charente-Maritime on the Atlantic coast, especially in work by France 3 Régions and France Info. They also describe what happened at the Paris Bar - the body that disciplines lawyers - after the papers linked François Gibault's name to the scandal. ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "Allegations are not convictions",
            "marks": [
              "em"
            ]
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": ". What matters next is how France answers when those claims keep moving with dates and file names attached, and when survivors speak on the record under their own names.",
            "marks": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "_type": "block",
        "style": "normal",
        "children": [
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "The story that caught fire is anchored in ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "Les hommes de la rue du Bac",
            "marks": [
              "em"
            ]
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": ", a ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "Libération (major French daily)",
            "marks": [
              "em"
            ]
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": " investigation into child sexual abuse, silence, and power in a wealthy Paris world - the seventh arrondissement, with “rue du Bac” shorthand for a tight social circle as much as a street. Alongside the newspaper work, ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "Willy Le Devin",
            "marks": [
              "em"
            ]
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": " has published ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "Les hommes de la rue du Bac",
            "marks": [
              "em"
            ]
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": " at ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "JC Lattès",
            "marks": [
              "em"
            ]
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": " (major Paris publishing house), described in broadcast interviews as built from her account and from documents connected to the family home.",
            "marks": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "_type": "block",
        "style": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "La Tribune Dimanche: three signatories",
            "marks": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "_type": "block",
        "style": "normal",
        "children": [
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "In May 2025, ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "La Tribune Dimanche (Sunday opinion section of the French business daily La Tribune)",
            "marks": [
              "em"
            ]
          },
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": " published an open letter under this headline:",
            "marks": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "_type": "block",
        "style": "blockquote",
        "children": [
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "« Réveillons-nous ! »",
            "marks": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "_type": "block",
        "style": "normal",
        "children": [
          {
            "_type": "span",
            "text": "<details class=\"translate\">",
            "marks": []
